  <h2>The Setup Problem</h2>

  <p>
    You bought a 3D printer. It showed up in a box. Maybe you assembled it from a kit. Maybe it came pre-assembled but needs calibration. Either way, you spent two weekends fighting with it, watched 40 YouTube videos, joined three Discord servers, and you're still getting spaghetti instead of parts.
  </p>

  <p>
    I hear this story constantly. 3D printers are not plug-and-play — not yet, anyway. There's a learning curve that the marketing doesn't mention. First-layer calibration alone has derailed more beginners than any other single thing in this hobby. And if you bought the printer for your business, those weekends of troubleshooting aren't a hobby — they're lost revenue.
  </p>

  <h2>The Service</h2>

  <p>
    We'll come to you. Anywhere in Canada, and select locations internationally. Here's what the service includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Assembly:</strong> If your printer came as a kit, we build it. Properly. Every bolt torqued, every belt tensioned, every connector seated. No loose wires, no skipped steps.</li>
    <li><strong>Calibration:</strong> First layer, flow rate, input shaping (if supported), PID tuning on the hotend and bed. We calibrate until the printer produces parts that meet spec.</li>
    <li><strong>Environment setup:</strong> We'll assess your space — power, ventilation, ambient temperature, vibration from nearby equipment — and make recommendations. A printer on a wobbly table next to an HVAC vent will never print well.</li>
    <li><strong>Training:</strong> Hands-on training with your printer. How to load filament, how to start a print, how to recognize common failures, how to use the slicer. We don't leave until you can run the machine yourself.</li>
    <li><strong>Material guidance:</strong> We'll help you stock the right filaments for your applications and show you how each one behaves differently.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who This Is For</h2>

  <p>
    This service isn't for people who enjoy tinkering. If you love the troubleshooting process, have at it — that's part of the hobby for a lot of people and I respect that.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is for:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Businesses</strong> that bought a printer to produce parts and can't afford weeks of learning curve.</li>
    <li><strong>Schools and makerspaces</strong> that need a printer set up correctly on day one for students to use.</li>
    <li><strong>Professionals</strong> — dentists, engineers, architects — who need the printer as a tool, not a project.</li>
    <li><strong>Anyone</strong> who tried to set it up themselves, got frustrated, and shelved the printer. We'll get it running.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why In-Person Matters</h2>

  <p>
    I know you can find setup guides online. I know there are remote troubleshooting services. Here's why in-person is different: I can see your environment. I can feel the belt tension. I can hear whether the bearings sound right. I can check that the frame is actually square — not "looks square on camera" square, but measured-with-a-machinist-square square.
  </p>

  <p>
    A 3D printer is a precision tool. Setting one up properly requires hands on the machine. No amount of Zoom calls replaces that.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Costs</h2>

  <p>
    The service is priced based on location and scope. A single printer setup in Atlantic Canada is straightforward. A fleet of five machines at a facility in Ontario is a bigger project. <a href="/contact">Contact us</a> with the details — what printer, where you are, what you need — and we'll quote it honestly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Travel is included in the price. You don't pay for flights and hotels on top of the service fee. One number, everything included, no surprises.
  </p>

  <h2>Stop Fighting Your Printer</h2>

  <p>
    A 3D printer that's properly set up is a joy to use. A 3D printer that isn't is a source of endless frustration. If yours is collecting dust because the setup defeated you, it doesn't have to stay that way. Let us come set it up right. You'll be printing quality parts before we drive away.
  </p>
</BlogLayout>
